<body>

<p><b><font size=3D"6">A 1.8-54 MHz 1KW RF Deck incorporating all=20
updates applied to the original through </font></b><font size=3D"6"><b>May =
2017</b></font></p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/52017-01.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"390"></p>
<p>This RF deck was developed on .078 thick FR4, and incorporates all the=
=20
changes made to the original one done on TC350 through May 2017. The perfor=
mance is the same=20
(same output power) with slightly lower gain, which results from the use of=
 a more effective gain=20
stabilizing circuit. These are the advantages to this design over the origi=
nal:</p>
<ul>
	<li>
	<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">The need for board spacers has been elimin=
ated</p>
	</li>
	<li>
	<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">A simpler heat spreader is used, cut from=
=20
	.375" flat copper plate</p>
	<ul>
		<li>
		<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">The heat spreader no longer requires a=20
		slot (for mounting the LDMOS) to be machined into the copper</p></li>
		<li>
		<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">heat spreader size is now the same as the=
=20
		board footprint (4 x 6.5"), is .375 thick, and has a bit more mass ( it=
=20
		weighs more than 3 pounds)</p></li>
		<li>
		<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">The heat spreader does not require tapped=
=20
		mounting holes; instead, it uses 12 pass-through holes designed to make=
=20
		the rf deck easier to construct and mount to a heat sink. The Aluminum=20
		heat sink is now the only piece requiring tapped mounting holes.</p>
		</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li>
	<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">Overall height has been reduced</p></li>
	<li>
	<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">The cost has been reduced</p></li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">Here's the schematic for this RF deck:</p>
<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/52017sch.jpg" width=3D"102=
4" height=3D"604"></p>
<p>If you are building this RF deck from a kit I supplied, here are the ass=
embly=20
instructions:</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-02.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"488" align=3D"left"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Begin with the output board, and install all of the capacitors to their=
=20
positions shown here<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-04.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"451" align=3D"left">Cut=20
two pieces of RG316 coax to a length of 14.5 inches (37cm). Pair them as sh=
own,=20
and wind them through one of the large ferrite cores, passing the paired co=
ax 4=20
times through the center of the core from left to right.</p>
<p>By using two pieces of identical 50 ohm coax like this in parallel, we a=
re=20
duplicating the characteristics of 25 ohm coax. At 50 MHz and below, this R=
G316=20
Teflon coax can handle more than 3 times the power it will actually need to=
=20
handle in this circuit.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-05.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"493" align=3D"left"></p>
<p>Remove 1/2" insulation from each of the 4 ends. Flare the shields back,=
=20
leaving about 5mm of the shields unflared; tin the unflared shields at the=
=20
location of the red arrow.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-06.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"199" align=3D"left">Trim=20
the flared parts of the shields away with a pair of diagonal cutters; this =
is=20
best done by holding the cutting blades parallel to the coax as the flared=
=20
portions are trimmed away.</p>
<p>Taking care not to cut into the center conductors (which weakens them),=
=20
remove all but 3mm of insulation from the ends as shown in the photo, and t=
in=20
the center conductors.</p>
<p>Prepare the second transformer in the same way as the first.<br clear=3D=
"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-07.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"480" align=3D"left">Install=20
the first transformer by soldering both cables at one end to the traces as=
=20
shown, center conductors to the bottom trace, shields to the top, making ce=
rtain=20
the insulated part of the center conductors is all that bridges the gap.<br=
 clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-08.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"553" align=3D"left">Solder=20
the other ends of the transformer across the vertical gap between the botto=
m two=20
traces, center conductors to the right side, shields to the left.<br clear=
=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-09.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"430" align=3D"left">Install=20
the second transformer to the right side in mirror image style in the same=
=20
manner as the first (see photo).<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/52017-02.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"566" align=3D"left"></p>
<p>Make the drain chokes; locate the two #14 tinned magnet wires, straighte=
n them out, and pass=20
each=20
through a ferrite core (Laird 28b1000-000) as shown here. One end should ex=
tend=20
out the end of a core by about an inch, the other by almost 2 inches. The w=
ire=20
should pass through the center of the core 9 times.</p>
<p><br clear=3D"all">
<br clear=3D"all">
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/52017-03.jpg" width=3D"640=
" height=3D"278" align=3D"left">This=20
photo shows how and where to mount these chokes. Leave as much space as pos=
sible=20
between them, about 1/8 inch is enough.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-12.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"318" align=3D"left">Construct=20
the output balun</p>
<p>The RG402 coax supplied should be trimmed to a length of 15.5 inches (39=
5mm)=20
(the extra 2 inches left over are provided for practicing how to safely tri=
m it,=20
which will be shown in a later step). Begin by passing the coax through the=
 core=20
from left to right, leaving about 1 inch coming out of the core on the left=
=20
side. After winding the coax so it passes through the center of the core 4=
=20
times, you'll have about 2.25 inches (57mm) coming out of the right side.<b=
r clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-13.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"480" align=3D"left"></p>
<p>Practice these next steps on the short piece of RG402 left over from=20
trimming; proceed with trimming the balun ends only when you feel you've=20
mastered the technique.</p>
<p>Remove 1/2 inch (12mm) insulation from each end, exposing the outer=20
conductor. Roll the coax under a knife blade to 'score' it, at 5mm away fro=
m the=20
insulation, taking care not to cut completely through the shield (outer).<b=
r clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-14.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"452" align=3D"left">Using=20
a pliers, bend the shield end back and forth, breaking it away at the score=
d=20
location. Once it is broken, it can be removed with a pair of diagonal cutt=
ers,=20
or just pulled away from the end of the cable. This needs to be done at bot=
h=20
ends of the balun.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-15.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"406" align=3D"left">On=20
both ends, remove all but 2 or 3mm of insulation from around the center=20
conductor, taking care not to cut into the center conductor itself. The bal=
un is=20
now ready to be installed.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-16.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"480" align=3D"left"><b>Disregard=20
the single bifilar-wound drain choke</b> in this and all the remaining phot=
os=20
(it is not the type being used now).</p>
<p>Beginning=20
with the longer lead, form the center conductor so it will lie flat on the =
trace=20
in plane with the outer, and solder it in place across the gap as shown; ce=
nter=20
conductor soldered to the left side, outer soldered to the right.</p>
<p><br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-17.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"519" align=3D"left">In=20
this last step, you'll need to bend the coax down and then level again as i=
t=20
exits the core, and secure the ends as shown. Solder the outer conductor fi=
rst,=20
then bend the center conductor down onto its trace and solder it in place.<=
/p>
<p>The output board is finished.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p>Continuing now with assembling the input board; install all components=
=20
(except T1) as shown in their locations below. The component locations for =
C5,=20
rtb1, C6 and rtb2 are not used in this design.</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-18.jpg" width=3D"=
1024" height=3D"536"><br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-19.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"480" align=3D"left">Cut=20
8 inches of RG316 and remove 5mm of insulation from the center,=20
exposing the shield in that location. Tin the shield there.<br clear=3D"all=
">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-20.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"480" align=3D"left">Remove=20
2.25 inches insulation from each end, exposing the shield.<br clear=3D"all"=
>
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-21.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"480" align=3D"left">Holding=20
the shield in place with your left hand, push the right end of the shield t=
o the=20
left, forming a mushroom bulge about 5mm away from the insulation on the le=
ft.=20
Tin the 5mm of shield at the spot referenced by the red arrow.<br clear=3D"=
all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-22.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"634" align=3D"left">Using=20
a pair of diagonal cutters with the cutting blades parallel to the coax, tr=
im=20
away the mushroom bulge and slide the loose shield off of and away from the=
=20
insulated center conductor.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-23.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"362" align=3D"left">Install=20
the coax into the smaller ferrite core in criss-cross fashion as shown.<br =
clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-24.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"480" align=3D"left">Position=20
the transformer as shown, and pass the coax on the left across the core to =
the=20
right, then through the core from right to&nbsp; left. Solder the exposed s=
hield=20
to the left gate trace, taking care not to bridge the gap between the trace=
s.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-25.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"334" align=3D"left">Pass=20
the coax on the right across the core to the left, then through the core fr=
om=20
left to right. Solder the exposed shield to the trace on the right, taking =
care=20
not to bridge the gap between the traces.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-26.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"345" align=3D"left">Taking=20
care not to cut into the center conductor, trim 4mm of insulation away from=
 the=20
ends and tin them. Solder the coax center tap to the trace below it (one en=
d of=20
R10 is also connected to this trace).<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-27.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"629" align=3D"left">Solder=20
the upper wire to the trace with R13, and the lower end to the ground trace=
 next=20
to C3. The input board is finished.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<h1>Installing the Boards to the Spreader and Heat Sink</h1>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-28.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"359" align=3D"left">Your=20
heat sink should be drilled/tapped for 40-40 machine screws (or your metric=
=20
equivalent) <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016%20dr=
ill%20template.pdf">using the=20
pattern in this template</a>.</p>
<p>Position your copper spreader (with LDMOS attached) over the drilled pat=
tern=20
in your heat sink.</p>
<p>The recommended way to attach your LDMOS to the copper spreader is to=20
flow-solder it as you see it pictured here. Machined spreaders with LDMOS=
=20
attached using this process are <a href=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/parts_i_can=
_provide.htm">available=20
on the parts page here</a>.</p>
<p>You can use screws to mount your LDMOS, but the heat transfer and rf=20
grounding will be inferior.<br clear=3D"all">
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-29.jpg" width=3D"=
640" height=3D"476" align=3D"left"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Slide the boards into place under the transistor tabs<br clear=3D"all">
<br clear=3D"all">
<img border=3D"0" src=3D"http://www.w6pql.com/hf/72016-30.jpg" width=3D"640=
" height=3D"389" align=3D"left"></p>
<p>Secure the board and spreader to the heat sink with 4-40 x 5/8 machine s=
crews=20
(or your metric equivalent) using flat washers under the screw heads. Once =
the=20
boards are in proper position, tighten the screws.</p>
<p>Solder the 4 transistor tabs to the PC boards. </p>
<h1><br clear=3D"all">
Recommended testing procedure</h1>
<h1><font size=3D"3">There is no tuning required with this amplifier, and o=
nly one=20
adjustment to make (setting idling current).</font></h1>
<ol>
	<li>Attach input and output coax jumpers. Your driver should be limited to=
=20
	3w on 160 through 10m, and 5w on 6m; the output should be on a dummy load =
for the initial testing.</li>
	<li>Attach ground, bias (12v?) and VDD (50v) wires to the RF deck, but do=
=20
	not apply power yet.<p>&nbsp;</p><ul>
		<li><b>CAUTION - for the initial test, you should place a 3 to 5 ohm 50w=
=20
		power resistor in series with the VDD, or use a current-limited power=20
		supply (limited to 5a). A fuse is not fast enough to protect against=20
		problems...if there is a short from a stray wire=20
		strand, or a weak capacitor lets go, it will create an arc powerful=20
		enough to vaporize board traces, transistor tabs, etc., long before a=20
		fuse can open up.</b></li>
	</ul>
	<p>&nbsp;</p></li>
	<li>
	<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">Turn on the 50v main supply voltage, but=
=20
		not the bias; there should be no current drawn</p></li>
	<li>
	<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">Turn on the bias and note the idling curre=
nt=20
	drawn from the <b>50v supply</b>.=20
	Adjust IDQ for 2 amps. <b>Note: the current drawn by the bias supply=20
	(usually12v) is not what you are measuring here...you must measure the=20
	idling current (IDQ) the LDMOS draws from the 50v supply.</b></p></li>
	<li>
	<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px">Shut off the power supply, and remove curr=
ent=20
	limiting.</p></li>
	<li>Turn the power supply back on; drive the amp with about 1/2w, and veri=
fy=20
	there is output power.</li>
	<li>If all OK in the previous step, the amplifier can now be driven to ful=
l=20
	output. Current should not be driven higher than 35 amps on any band. Chec=
k=20
	the performance graph in the main technical article for typical performanc=
e.</li>
</ol>




</body></html>
